# A user-facing change lands in the guides and the skill

Two surfaces ship out of this repo to people who don't read our code, and both
go stale **silently** — nothing fails when they're wrong:

- **`docs/guides/*.md`** — canonical for humans, and the website's actual
  content: `website/` renders them into its bundle at build time
  (`website/scripts/render-content.ts`), and `.github/workflows/deploy-docs.yml`
  redeploys the site whenever `docs/guides/**` changes on main. Editing a guide
  *is* shipping a site change; no generated file to commit.
- **`skills/prisma-composer/SKILL.md`** — the agent-condensed mirror, installed
  into other people's repos (`npx skills add`). An agent reading a stale skill
  writes wrong code and blames the framework.

**If your PR changes what a user can observe, update both in the same PR.**
`docs/design/**` is for us; landing an ADR is not documenting.

## What counts

- A new / changed / removed export, param, facet, or type reachable from a
  `packages/9-public/*` entry — anything an app author writes.
- A CLI command, flag, or its output.
- **Behaviour a user hits without changing a line of their code** — a new
  default, failure mode, or status code. The most-missed case: RPC endpoints
  began returning `401` to unwired callers, and for a while neither surface said
  so, which reads as a broken deploy.
- A testing seam (`mockService` / `bootstrapService`) or a constraint on it.
- A platform gotcha a user will hit and misdiagnose.

**Not:** internal refactors, `@internal/*` moves, tests, ADRs, design docs. If
nothing an app author does or sees changes, skip both.

## How

- **The guides are canonical; the skill is the mirror.** Write the explanation
  once in the guide, then teach an agent the same fact tersely. They must not
  disagree.
- **Document the consequence, not just the feature.** The line worth writing is
  the one that stops a bug report — *why the thing they just tried returns
  401* — not that a mechanism exists.
- **Read `skills/README.md` before editing the skill.** It has its own binding
  rules: verify every claim against a real export map / the CLI (if ripgrep
  can't find it, it doesn't ship), stay self-contained (no link may resolve
  outside `skills/prisma-composer/`), teach concepts not procedures.
- A new guide needs no registration — `website/tests/content.test.ts` asserts
  one rendered guide per `docs/guides/*.md` and that every in-site link
  resolves, so a broken cross-link fails CI.
